<h2 id="reading">Reading</h2>
<ul>
  <li>
    <p>If you have 10 minutes, read this blog post - itâ€™s very easy to read, itâ€™s recent (as of 18th July, 2018), and gives an overall perspective of why causal inference might be a good framework to try - <a href="https://www.inference.vc/untitled/">[blog]</a></p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>If you have an hour to spare, read <em>The Art and Science of Cause and Effect</em> by Judea Pearl.
This is the transcript of a public lecture by Judea Pearl
delivered November 1996, and it brilliantly motivates why we need
causality, and gives an overview of what the theory
allows us to do.  <a href="http://bayes.cs.ucla.edu/BOOK-2K/causality2-epilogue.pdf">[pdf]</a></p>
  </li>
  <li>If you have 8-10 hours to spare, and want to get into some level of detail, read Cosma Shaliziâ€™s lecture notes for the course on Advanced Data Analysis
    <ul>
      <li>Graphical Causal Models <a href="http://www.stat.cmu.edu/~cshalizi/uADA/12/lectures/ch22.pdf">[pdf]</a></li>
      <li>Identifying Causal Effects from Observations <a href="http://www.stat.cmu.edu/~cshalizi/uADA/12/lectures/ch23.pdf">[pdf]</a></li>
      <li>Estimating Causal Effects from Observations <a href="http://www.stat.cmu.edu/~cshalizi/uADA/12/lectures/ch24.pdf">[pdf]</a></li>
      <li>Discovering Causal Structure from Observations <a href="http://www.stat.cmu.edu/~cshalizi/uADA/12/lectures/ch25.pdf">[pdf]</a></li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>If you want to understand Causality in depth, read <em>Elements of Causal Inference</em> by Jonas Peters, Dominik Janzing, Bernhard SchÃ¶lkopf.
Free PDF available <a href="https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/elements-causal-inference">[here].</a></p>
  </li>
  <li>If you have a lot of time to spare, then read Judea Pearlâ€™s classic book
<em>Causality</em> <a href="https://www.amazon.in/Causality-Judea-Pearl/dp/052189560X">[amazon]</a></li>
</ul>

